I am arguing that you were NEVER supposed to be a &quot;tank&quot; in the definition of tank being the person in a group who's job was to have and keep aggro while the damage dealers killed it.  Were you supposed to be a tank, you'd have gotten this skill called &quot;taunt&quot;.  I'd argue that rangers were supposed to be better tanks than monks, much less warriors, Paladins, and Shadowknights.    They all have a means of gaining aggro where you don't.  Due to this, you were NEVER supposed to have your role as a &quot;tank&quot;.   What some pathetic writer in a blurb in a guide which devotes more time to dieties than class balance says is irrelevant.  <br>
<br>
Your premise that you were somehow with lower HP, lower AC, and no ability to GAIN aggro only to lose it, you were designed to be a &quot;tank&quot; is fatally flawed and has no real in-game basis.   You are, and were ALWAYS supposed to be a damage dealer with good avoidance who gets HURT when you get hit.  The gear imbalance is true, but it causes a game imbalance.   The fact that you wield crap from Kunark has no relevance on the fact that insane ratio weapons for monks drop and have since Kunark, as a matter of fact, the Rune Fighter's Staff has better Dmg/Dly than a warrior's epic.   This is NOTHING compared to certain VP weapons of 2 expansions ago, or of Khatars of today.  You are a damage class, and should be hurt MASSIVELY when you get hit, that's the concept behind a monk and has always been.  <br>
<br>
Just because you stamp your feet, make silly claims like that you had comparable AC pre-kunark, which was totally untrue, and quote a user guide doesn't make your claim right.   Monks aren't, weren't, and should never be &quot;tanks&quot;.<br>
