et several VERY useful abilities.<br>
<br>
Yes the taunt key is the major difference between a Warrior and a Monk.  If gaining agro is the concern though, who wouldn't use one of the Knights for better agro control since they do it so much better?<br>
<br>
So in the end you can have one of three tanks.<br>
<br>
Monks - Moderate agro control issues, high damage absorbtion, deals a lot of damage and has some other utility.<br>
<br>
Warriors - Modest agro control issues, high damage absorbtion, deals out moderate amounts of damage, and NO other utility.<br>
<br>
Knights - No agro control issues,  moderate to high damage absorbition, deals out modest amounts of damage, and significant utility.<br>
<br>
Monks are superior to Warriors in damage dealing and about equal on damage absorbtion.  Their damage dealing actually gives them solid agro control, but they have issues gaining agro initially.<br>
<br>
Knights have superior agro control and have little to no problem gaining agro initially.  They don't absorb damage quite as well as Warriors and their damage is equal to or slightly less than Warriors, depending on weapons used.  They do have very high utility though.<br>
<br>
So where exactly do Warriors shine?  Yes, I know, defensive makes us 'the' raid tank.  But outside of that, for normal groups?  Inferior agro control to Knights.  Inferior agro control to Monks, really, beyond initial gaining of agro.  About equal damage absorbtion to Monks.  Slightly superior damage absorbtion to Knights.  Grosely inferior damage dealing to Monks.  About equal damage dealing to Knights (sometimes less, sometimes more, many variables involved).  And completely inferior utility.<br>
<br>
Seems like many more minuses than pluses.  And in those few areas we do have pluses, they aren't major pluses.<br>
